{"title_page": "Joe Mesi", "text_new": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{Infobox boxer|name=Joe Mesi\n|image= <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] -->|\n| realname =Joe Mesi\n| nickname=Baby Joe\n|weight=[[Heavyweight]]\n|nationality = American\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1973|11|27|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Tonawanda (town), New York|Tonawanda, New York]], United States\n|style=Orthodox\n|total=36\n|wins=36\n|KO=29\n|losses=0\n|draws=0\n|no contests=0\n|}}\n\n'''\"Baby\" Joe Mesi''' (born November 27, 1973) is an American retired [[Boxing|boxer]] and politician from [[Tonawanda, New York]]. He is a registered member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\n== Early life ==\nJoe grew up in [[City of Tonawanda|Tonawanda, New York]], a suburb of [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]. He attended [[Sweet Home High School (Amherst, New York)|Sweet Home High School]] in [[Amherst, New York]]. He did not start his boxing career until he was about 19 years of age.\n\n== Boxing career ==\nHe was a New York State [[Golden Gloves]] champion, and as an amateur boxer he defeated future two-time Heavyweight champion [[Hasim Rahman]].  Mesi made it all the way to the finals in the 1996 Olympic Trials, but lost to eventual US heavyweight representative Lawrence Clay-Bey.  In Buffalo, for a brief period, Joe was once considered by some to be the city's \"third professional franchise\", with the [[Buffalo Sabres]] and [[Buffalo Bills]] being the other two.  Joe is still often seen at Bills and Sabres games and also supports many local charities.\n\n=== Philanthropy ===\nIn 2002, Mesi started a non-profit to raise awareness about organ donation and transplantation upon finding out his cousin was in need of a kidney transplant, and to help others in the Upstate New York area who needed such surgeries. His cousin, Ganelle Shanor, died in an accident before she was able to receive the operation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.babyjoemesi.com/foundation.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-05-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206074408/http://babyjoemesi.com/foundation.htm |archivedate=2016-02-06 }}</ref> In January 2004, Mesi donated $7,500 to the Golisano Children's Hospital in Rochester, New York as a way of giving back to the Rochester community and to promote an upcoming fight at the Blue Cross Arena, with kidney transplant recipient Dillon Gonzalez and his family in attendance. The foundation was funded in part by admission fees to victory parties.<ref>https://www.urmc.rochester.edu/news/story/466/boxer-baby-joe-mesi-visits-golisano-childrens-hospital.aspx</ref>\n\n=== Injury and suspension ===\nMesi's promising boxing career was set back greatly when an MRI indicated he had suffered at least one, perhaps two [[subdural hematoma]]s <ref>http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/sports/3299563.html</ref>\n\nThe injuries came from a 2004 bout with former cruiserweight champion [[Vassiliy Jirov]]. In round 9,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.muaylok.net/boxingrec/index.php?id=167 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325185242/http://www.muaylok.net/boxingrec/index.php?id=167 |archivedate=2012-03-25 }}</ref><ref>http://wn.com/Vassily_Jirov</ref> Mesi was knocked down from a right hook and in the tenth round he was knocked down two more times. Mesi managed to finish the fight on his feet and the bout was scored 94-93 for Mesi by all three judges (i.e., won by [[unanimous decision]]),\n\nIn June 2005, Mesi, along with his attorneys and three doctors supporting his reinstatement, went before the [[Nevada State Athletic Commission]] to argue Mesi's hematomas had healed, and, he was, \"in no more danger than any other boxer.\"  Mesi's appeal was denied by a 5-0 vote.  In response to Dr. Julian E. Bailes, chairman of the department of neurosurgery at the [[West Virginia University School of Medicine]], opinion that -  \"Football players and other athletes who had even more severe head injuries than Mesi were allowed to continue their careers without further harmful effects.\" - Dr. Tony Alamo, one of the board's commissioners, replied, \"You play football, you don't play boxing.\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/21/sports/othersports/suspension-upheld-but-boxer-is-fighting-it.html | work=The New York Times | title=Suspension Upheld But Boxer Is Fighting It | date=15 July 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe suspension effectively [[blacklist]]ed him from boxing anywhere in the United States under the premise of the [[full faith and credit clause]]. He launched several ineffective lawsuits against parties they claimed had 'leaked' news of his health, while also appealing to Nevada representatives that he should be allowed to box. The suspension was officially lifted when Mesi's Nevada boxing license expired at the end of 2005.  However, he was unable to renew the license due to the concerns of Nevada boxing officials.  Mesi has since been licensed by the [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] Boxing Commission in February 2006, the [[Louisiana]] State Boxing Commission in June 2006, the [[Arkansas]] State Boxing Commission in August 2006, the [[Michigan]] State Boxing Commission in September 2006, the [[West Virginia]] State Boxing Commission in February 2007, and the [[Rhode Island]] State Boxing Commission in October 2007.\n\nJoe Mesi has one of the longest active undefeated professional boxing records in the world for a heavyweight. Ranked #1 heavyweight contender by the WBC prior to his two-year layoff, Mesi was #16 in the December 2007 rankings.<ref name=\"mesiranking\">{{cite news\n |url=http://www.wbcboxing.com/WBCboxing/portal/cfpages/contentmgr.cfm?docId=94&docTipo=4&orderby=docid&sortby=ASC \n |publisher=World Boxing Council \n |title=WBC Heavyweight Ratings \n |date=October 13, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070810070242/http://www.wbcboxing.com/WBCboxing/Portal/cfpages/contentmgr.cfm?docId=94&docTipo=4&orderby=docid&sortby=ASC \n |archivedate=August 10, 2007 \n}}</ref> He has not actively boxed since 2007, having instead turned to politics.\n\n==Political career==\n\nOn February 14, 2008, Mesi publicly expressed his interest to run for the [[New York State Senate]].  He attempted to fill the 61st District seat vacated by [[Mary Lou Rath]].<ref name=\"mesisenate\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/home/story/275969.html\n|publisher=The Buffalo News\n|title=Heavyweight contender Joe Mesi considers run for state Senate\n|author=Robert J. McCarthy\n|date=February 14, 2008\n}}</ref> He won the Democratic primary for the seat on September 9, 2008.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/boxer-joe-mesi-one-step-closer-to-senate-seat-1.765573 | work=CBC Sports | title=Boxer Joe Mesi One Step Closer To Senate Seat | date=15 July 2019}}</ref>\nMesi lost the general election to Republican [[Michael Ranzenhofer]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/home/story/484613.html\n|publisher=The Buffalo News\n|title=State Senate: Ranzenhofer, Stachowski, Volker win\n|author=Phil Fairbanks\n|date=November 5, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nMost recently, Joe has taken a position with the Democratic Senate Majority heading up a local Buffalo liaison office.  \nMesi's name was circulated as a potential Democratic candidate to replace the retiring [[James P. Hayes|Jim Hayes]] in the [[New York State Assembly]]. The assembly seat was won by Raymond Walter.\n\n==Professional boxing record <ref>http://boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=016554&cat=boxer</ref>==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|ko-wins=29\n|ko-losses=0\n|dec-wins=7\n|dec-losses=0\n}}\n{{s-start}}\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#e3e3e3;\"\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Result'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none none solid solid; \"|'''Record'''\n|  style=\"border-style:none non