pplying to professional boxers in the State of [[Nevada]] which would allow Mesi to apply to fight in [[Nevada]] again (previously not so)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.babyjoemesi.com BabyJoeMesi.com] \u2013 Official website of Joe Mesi (Currently Down)\n* {{Boxrec|id=016554}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[North American Boxing Federation|NABF]] [[Heavyweight]] champion\n | years  = June 24, 2003 \u2013 October 30, 2003 <br> '''Vacates'''\n | before = [[Eliecer Castillo]] <br> '''Vacant'''\n | after  = [[Eliecer Castillo]]\n}}\n{{s-bef|before=Vacant}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[World Boxing Council|WBC]] USNBC Heavyweight Champion|years=October 12, 2007\u2013present}} <br> '''Vacates'''\n{{s-inc|after=[[Ray Austin (boxer)|Ray Austin]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mesi, Joe}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight boxers]]\n[[Category:Italian male boxers]]\n[[Category:American boxers of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Erie Community College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Tonawanda, New York]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n", "name_user": "Jjjuuussstttiiinnn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePhilanthropy:ADDED comma in dollar amount", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Mesi"}
{"title_page": "Health and Sports Day", "text_new": "{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name  = Health and Sports Day\n|type          = national\n|image         = \u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5 sports day 2011 in Nihonmatsu, Fukushima (6294102369).jpg\n|imagesize     = 250px\n|caption       = A cycling event for Health and Sports Day (\u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5) in 2011 near the city of [[Nihonmatsu, Fukushima]]\n|official_name = Health and Sports Day\n|nickname      = Health-Sports Day<br/>Sports Day\n|observedby    = Japan\n|litcolor      = \n|longtype      = National\n|significance  = commemorates the opening of the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]]\n|scheduling               = nth weekday of the month\n|duration                 = 1 day\n|frequency                = annual year \n|week_ordinal              = second\n|weekday                   = Monday\n|month                     = October\n|date2020 = July 24\n|celebrations  = \n|observances   = \n|relatedto     =\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Health and Sports Day'''|\u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5|''Taiiku no hi''}}, also known as '''Health-Sports Day''' or '''Sports Day''', is a [[Holidays of Japan|national holiday]] in [[Japan]] held annually on the second Monday in October. It commemorates the opening of the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] held in [[Tokyo]], and exists to promote sports and an active lifestyle.<ref>https://www.japan-talk.com/jt/new/health-and-sports-day</ref>\n\n==History and current practice==\nThe first  [[Health]] and [[Sport]]s Day was held on October 10, 1966, two years after the [[1964 Summer Olympics]].  October was chosen for the unusually late Summer Olympics to avoid the Japanese [[Wet season|rainy season]], and Health and Sports Day continues to be one of the fairest days of the year.<ref name=\"kidsweb_sports\">[http://web-jpn.org/kidsweb/explore/calendar/october/sports.html Kid's Web Japan: Sports Day], retrieved November 21, 2005</ref>\n\nIn 2000, as a result of the [[Happy Monday Seido]], Health and Sports Day was moved to the second Monday in October.<ref name=\"consulate\">[http://www.cgj.org/en/c/vol_12-3/title_04.html Consulate General of Japan in New York: Health Sports Day in Japan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211040517/http://www.cgj.org/en/c/vol_12-3/title_04.html |date=2006-02-11 }}, retrieved November 21, 2005</ref>\n\nAs Health and Sports Day is a day to promote sports and physical and mental health, many{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} schools and businesses choose this day to hold their annual {{nihongo|''Field Day''|\u904b\u52d5\u4f1a|Und\u014d-kai}}, or [[sports day]]. This typically consists of a range of physical events ranging from more traditional track-and-field events such as the [[100 metres]] or [[4 x 100 metres relay]] to more uncommon events such as the [[tug of war]] and the {{nihongo|\"[[kiba-sen|Cavalry Battle]]\"|\u9a0e\u99ac\u6226|kiba-sen}}.\n\nMost communities and schools across Japan celebrate Sports Day with a sports festival which is similar to a mini Olympics. These festivals include many of the traditional track and field events, such as 4 \u00d7 100 m [[relay]], 100m [[Sprint (running)|sprinting]], and [[long jump]], as well as many other events. Some of the events include: ball toss, tug-o-war, [[rugby football|rugby]]-ball dribbling races, [[sack race]]s, and so on.{{cn|date=October 2019}} Another common event is often simply called the \u201cexciting relay\u201d, which is an [[obstacle course]] relay including any number of different challenges: [[Three-legged race]]s, making a stretcher with a blanket and [[bamboo]] poles and then carrying an \u201cinjured\u201d teammate, laundry hanging, crawling on hands and knees under a net, and doing [[Cartwheel (gymnastics)|cartwheel]]s across a mat.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe festival usually begins <!--around 8:30 am (everywhere across the nation? this seems dubious-->with a parade featuring all the different teams that will be participating: it could be divided by neighbourhood, class, geographic area, or school. There is sometimes a local [[marching band]] providing music. Once the parade has gone around the field and lined up in the middle, the band will play [[Kimigayo]] and the [[Japanese flag]] will be raised. Local officials will make speeches welcoming everyone. Often everyone will spread out across the grounds for group [[stretching]] (this stretching routine was developed by the government and is done daily by many Japanese people; the stretching routine music is broadcast daily on the radio and TV). Then it is time to start the events.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn 2020, Health and Sports Day will be permanently renamed {{Nihongo|Sports Day|\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u306e\u65e5|Sup\u014dtsu no hi}}. For 2020 only, Sports Day will be held on July 24, to coincide with the opening of the [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Tokyo Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tokyo-np.co.jp/article/sports/list/201806/CK2018061302000237.html|title=\u795d\u65e5\u79fb\u3057\u4e94\u8f2a\u6e0b\u6ede\u7de9\u548c\u3000\u300c\u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5\u300d\u306f\u300c\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u306e\u65e5\u300d\u306b|work=\u6771\u4eac\u65b0\u805e TOKYO Web|access-date=2018-06-22|language=ja-JP}}</ref>{{dead link|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081120201339/http://www.sse-franchise.com/soapbox/200810/12/what-is-sports-day/ What is sports day?]\n\n{{Japan Holidays}}\n\n[[Category:Public holidays in Japan]]\n[[Category:1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:October observances]]\n[[Category:Monday observances]]\n[[Category:Holidays and observances by scheduling (nth weekday of the month)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name  = Health and Sports Day\n|type          = national\n|image         = \u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5 sports day 2011 in Nihonmatsu, Fukushima (6294102369).jpg\n|imagesize     = 250px\n|caption       = A cycling event for Health and Sports Day (\u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5) in 2011 near the city of [[Nihonmatsu, Fukushima]]\n|official_name = Health and Sports Day\n|nickname      = Health-Sports Day<br/>Sports Day\n|observedby    = Japan\n|litcolor      = \n|longtype      = National\n|significance  = commemorates the opening of the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]]\n|scheduling               = nth weekday of the month\n|duration                 = 1 day\n|frequency                = annual year \n|week_ordinal              = second\n|weekday                   = Monday\n|month                     = October\n|date2021 = July 23\n|celebrations  = \n|observances   = \n|relatedto     =\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Health and Sports Day'''|\u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5|''Taiiku no hi''}}, also known as '''Health-Sports Day''' or '''Sports Day''', is a [[Holidays of Japan|national holiday]] in [[Japan]] held annually on the second Monday in October. It commemorates the opening of the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] held in [[Tokyo]], and exists to promote sports and an active lifestyle.<ref>https://www.japan-talk.com/jt/new/health-and-sports-day</ref>\n\n==History and current practice==\nThe first  [[Health]] and [[Sport]]s Day was held on October 10, 1966, two years after the [[1964 Summer Olympics]].  October was chosen for the unusually late Summer Olympics to avoid the Japanese [[Wet season|rainy season]], and Health and Sports Day continues to be one of the fairest days of the year.<ref name=\"kidsweb_sports\">[http://web-jpn.org/kidsweb/explore/calendar/october/sports.html Kid's Web Japan: Sports Day], retrieved November 21, 2005</ref>\n\nIn 2000, as a result of the [[Happy Monday Seido]], Health and Sports Day was moved to the second Monday in October.<ref name=\"consulate\">[http://www.cgj.org/en/c/vol_12-3/title_04.html Consulate General of Japan in New York: Health Sports Day in Japan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211040517/http://www.cgj.org/en/c/vol_12-3/title_04.html |date=2006-02-11 }}, retrieved November 21, 2005</ref>\n\nAs Health and Sports Day is a day to promote sports and physical and mental health, many{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} schools and businesses choose this day to hold their annual {{nihongo|''Field Day''|\u904b\u52d5\u4f1a|Und\u014d-kai}}, or [[sports day]]. This typically consists of a range of physical events ranging from more traditional track-and-field events such as the [[100 metres]] or [[4 x 100 metres relay]] to more uncommon events such as the [[tug of war]] and the {{nihongo|\"[[kiba-sen|Cavalry Battle]]\"|\u9a0e\u99ac\u6226|kiba-sen}}.\n\nMost communities and schools across Japan celebrate Sports Day with a sports festival which is similar to a mini Olympics. These festivals include many of the traditional track and field events, such as 4 \u00d7 100 m [[relay]], 100m [[Sprint (running)|sprinting]], and [[long jump]], as well as many other events. Some of the events include: ball toss, tug-o-war, [[rugby football|rugby]]-ball dribbling races, [[sack race]]s, and so on.{{cn|date=October 2019}} Another common event is often simply called the \u201cexciting relay\u201d, which is an [[obstacle course]] relay including any number of different challenges: [[Three-legged race]]s, making a stretcher with a blanket and [[bamboo]] poles and then carrying an \u201cinjured\u201d teammate, laundry hanging, crawling on hands and knees under a net, and doing [[Cartwheel (gymnastics)|cartwheel]]s across a mat.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe festival usually begins <!--around 8:30 am (everywhere across the nation? this seems dubious-->with a parade featuring all the different teams that will be participating: it could be divided by neighbourhood, class, geographic area, or school. There is sometimes a local [[marching band]] providing music. Once the parade has gone around the field and lined up in the middle, the band will play [[Kimigayo]] and the [[Japanese flag]] will be raised. Local officials will make speeches welcoming everyone. Often everyone will spread out across the grounds for group [[stretching]] (this stretching routine was developed by the government and is done daily by many Japanese people; the stretching routine music is broadcast daily on the radio and TV). Then it is time to start the events.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn 2021, Health and Sports Day will be permanently renamed {{Nihongo|Sports Day|\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u306e\u65e5|Sup\u014dtsu no hi}}. For 2021 only, Sports Day will be held on July 23, to coincide with the opening of the [[2020 Summer Olympics|2021 Tokyo Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tokyo-np.co.jp/article/sports/list/201806/CK2018061302000237.html|title=\u795d\u65e5\u79fb\u3057\u4e94\u8f2a\u6e0b\u6ede\u7de9\u548c\u3000\u300c\u4f53\u80b2\u306e\u65e5\u300d\u306f\u300c\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u306e\u65e5\u300d\u306b|work=\u6771\u4eac\u65b0\u805e TOKYO Web|access-date=2018-06-22|language=ja-JP}}</ref>{{dead link|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081120201339/http://www.sse-franchise.com/soapbox/200810/12/what-is-sports-day/ What is sports day?]\n\n{{Japan Holidays}}\n\n[[Category:Public holidays in Japan]]\n[[Category:1964 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:October observances]]\n[[Category:Monday observances]]\n[[Category:Holidays and observances by scheduling (nth weekday of the month)]]\n", "name_user": "Call me when you get the chance", "label": "safe", "comment": "Revert", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Health_and_Sports_Day"}
{"title_page": "Father Is a Bachelor", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Father Is a Bachelor\n| image_size     =\n| image\t         = Father Is a Bachelor FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Abby Berlin]]<br>[[Norman Foster (director)|Norman Foster]]\n| producer       = [[S. Sylvan Simon]]\n| screenplay     = [[Aleen Leslie]]<br>[[James Edward Grant]] \n| story          = [[James Edward Grant]]\n| starring       = [[William Holden]]<br>[[Coleen Gray]]\n| music          = Arthur Morton\n| cinematography = [[Burnett Guffey]]\n| editing        = Jerome Thoms\n| studio         = Columbia Pictures \n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1950|2|22}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Father Is a Bachelor''''' is a 1950 American [[comedy film|comedy]] [[family film|family]] [[romance film]] directed by [[Abby Berlin]] and [[Norman Foster (director)|Norman Foster]] and starring [[William Holden]] and [[Coleen Gray]].\n\n==Plot==\nCarefree vagabond Johnny Rutledge is stuck in a small town when his [[medicine show]] employer and friend Professor Mordecai Ford is put in jail. He befriends a five-year-old girl named May Chalotte and her brothers January (\"Jan\"), February (\"Feb\") and twins March and April. The children's parents died in a riverboat accident six months before, but Jan has not told anybody but Feb, and now Johnny, fearing they would be sent to an orphanage. Johnny makes it clear that he is adamantly opposed to taking on any responsibilities, but somehow finds himself becoming their \"uncle\" anyway. He works on a farm during the week and sings and waits tables on Sunday in a restaurant owned by Jericho Schlosser to provide for the children.\n\nWhen Prudence Millett, daughter of the local judge, comes to inquire why the boys are not in school, Johnny is forced to claim he is their uncle. A romance begins to blossom, despite his determination to remain free of entanglements.\n\nWhen wealthy, unloved Jeffrey Gilland Sr. orders Johnny to keep his disreputable children away from his son Jeffrey Jr., Johnny scuffles with him and gets arrested. He is bailed out by Prudence, but his troubles are not over. Plato Cassin, Gilland's lawyer, finds out about the children's parents and blackmails Johnny into agreeing to marry one of his older, spinster sisters, Genevieve and Adelaide, in order to keep the kids. (Adelaide wins a game of [[quoits]] for the privilege.) Plato also convinces Prudence that Johnny was using the children to romance her.\n\nAfter thinking it over, Johnny decides to run away with the now-released Professor Ford. May overhears and invites people to her birthday party the next day, intending it to be a going-away party for Johnny. Meanwhile, Johnny dissuades Gilland's young son from running away himself. At the party, a grateful Gilland drops the charges against him. \n\nPrudence shows up, having seen how far Johnny is willing to go for the children. When May says she would rather have her for an aunt, Prudence agrees wholeheartedly. Johnny tells Adelaide that he loves Prudence. She proves to be a sport and the two women gamble for him. Professor Ford offers what he and Johnny believe is Johnny's two-headed coin. Prudence wins the toss. Later, Johnny is shocked to learn that they accidentally used a regular coin.  \n\nProfessor Ford leaves town, leaving Johnny with his new family.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[William Holden]] as Johnny Rutledge\n* [[Coleen Gray]] as Prudence Millett\n* Mary Jane Saunders as May Chalotte\n* [[Charles Winninger]] as Professor Mordecai Ford\n* [[Stuart Erwin]] as Constable Pudge Barnham\n* [[Clinton Sundberg]] as Plato Cassin\n* [[Gary Gray (actor)|Gary Gray]] as Jan Chalotte\n* [[Sig Ruman]] as Jericho Schlosser\n* [[Billy Gray (actor)|Billy Gray]] as Feb Chalotte\n* [[Lloyd Corrigan]] as Judge Millett\n* Frederic Tozere as Jeffrey Gilland Sr.\n* Peggy Converse as Genevieve Cassin\n* Lillian Bronson as Adelaide Cassin\n\n==Songs==\nJohnny sings a number of songs in the film, including performing in [[blackface]] in the opening scene. Holden's singing was dubbed by [[Buddy Clark]].\n\n==Reception==\n[[Bosley Crowther]] called the film a \"saccharine, paper-thin little romance\" in his ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' review.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/23/archives/the-screen-six-newcomers-mark-holiday-capitols-malaya-has-tracy-and.html |title=The Screen: Six Newcomers Mark Holiday; Capitol's 'Malaya' Has Tracy and Stewart in Leads-- Two Imports Offered Walt Disney's Feature-Length 'Cinderella,' at the Mayfair, Heads List of Arrivals At the Capitol At the Criterion At the Rialto At the Palace At 55th St. Playhouse |author=Bosley Crowther |date=February 23, 1950 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\t\n\n== External links ==\n* {{tcmdb title|id=15982}}\n* {{IMDb title|0042449|Father Is a Bachelor}}\n* {{amg movie|91116}}\n* {{AFI film|id=26310|title=Father Is a Bachelor}}\n\n{{Norman Foster}}\n[[Category:1950 films]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about orphans]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Father Is a Bachelor\n| image_size     =\n| image\t         = Father Is a Bachelor FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Abby Berlin]]<br>[[Norman Foster (director)|Norman Foster]]\n| producer       = [[S. Sylvan Simon]]\n| screenplay     = [[Aleen Leslie]]<br>[[James Edward Grant]] \n| story          = [[James Edward Grant]]\n| starring       = [[William Holden]]<br>[[Coleen Gray]]\n| music          = Arthur Morton\n| cinematography = [[Burnett Guffey]]\n| editing        = Jerome Thoms\n| studio         = Columbia Pictures \n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1950|2|22}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Father Is a Bachelor''''' is a 1950 American [[comedy film|comedy]] [[family film|family]] [[romance film]] directed by [[Abby Berlin]] and [[Norman Foster (director)|Norman Foster]] and starring [[William Holden]] and [[Coleen Gray]].\n\n==Plot==\nCarefree vagabond Johnny Rutledge is stuck in a small town when his [[medicine show]] employer and friend Professor Mordecai Ford is put in jail. He befriends a five-year-old girl named May Chalotte and her brothers January (\"Jan\"), February (\"Feb\") and twins March and April. The children's parents died in a riverboat accident six months before, but Jan has not told anybody but Feb, and now Johnny, fearing they would be sent to an orphanage. Johnny makes it clear that he is adamantly opposed to taking on any responsibilities, but somehow finds himself becoming their \"uncle\" anyway. He works on a farm during the week and sings and waits tables on Sunday in a restaurant owned by Jericho Schlosser to provide for the children.\n\nWhen Prudence Millett, daughter of the local judge, comes to inquire why the boys are not in school, Johnny is forced to claim he is their uncle. A romance begins to blossom, despite his determination to remain free of entanglements.\n\nWhen wealthy, unloved Jeffrey Gilland Sr. orders Johnny to keep his disreputable children away from his son Jeffrey Jr., Johnny scuffles with him and gets arrested. He is bailed out by Prudence, but his troubles are not over. Plato Cassin, Gilland's lawyer, finds out about the children's parents and blackmails Johnny into agreeing to marry one of his older, spinster sisters, Genevieve and Adelaide, in order to keep the kids. (Adelaide wins a game of [[quoits]] for the privilege.) Plato also convinces Prudence that Johnny was using the children to romance her.\n\nAfter thinking it over, Johnny decides to run away with the now-released Professor Ford. May overhears and invites people to her birthday party the next day, intending it to be a going-away party for Johnny. Meanwhile, Johnny dissuades Gilland's young son from running away himself. At the party, a grateful Gilland drops the charges against him. \n\nPrudence shows up, having seen how far Johnny is willing to go for the children. When May says she would rather have her for an aunt, Prudence agrees wholeheartedly. Johnny tells Adelaide that he loves Prudence. She proves to be a sport and the two women gamble for him. Professor Ford offers what he and Johnny believe is Johnny's two-headed coin. Prudence wins the toss. Later, Johnny is shocked to learn that they accidentally used a regular coin.  \n\nProfessor Ford leaves town, leaving Johnny with his new family.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[William Holden]] as Johnny Rutledge\n* [[Coleen Gray]] as Prudence Millett\n* Mary Jane Saunders as May Chalotte\n* [[Charles Winninger]] as Professor Mordecai Ford\n* [[Stuart Erwin]] as Constable Pudge Barnham\n* [[Clinton Sundberg]] as Plato Cassin\n* [[Gary Gray (actor)|Gary Gray]] as Jan Chalotte\n* [[Sig Ruman]] as Jericho Schlosser\n* [[Billy Gray (actor)|Billy Gray]] as Feb Chalotte\n* [[Lloyd Corrigan]] as Judge Millett\n* Frederic Tozere as Jeffrey Gilland Sr.\n* Peggy Converse as Genevieve Cassin\n* Lillian Bronson as Adelaide Cassin\n\n==Songs==\nJohnny sings a number of songs in the film, including in the opening scene in [[blackface]]. Holden's singing was dubbed by [[Buddy Clark]].\n\n==Reception==\n[[Bosley Crowther]] called the film a \"saccharine, paper-thin little romance\" in his ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' review.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/23/archives/the-screen-six-newcomers-mark-holiday-capitols-malaya-has-tracy-and.html |title=The Screen: Six Newcomers Mark Holiday; Capitol's 'Malaya' Has Tracy and Stewart in Leads-- Two Imports Offered Walt Disney's Feature-Length 'Cinderella,' at the Mayfair, Heads List of Arrivals At the Capitol At the Criterion At the Rialto At the Palace At 55th St. Playhouse |author=Bosley Crowther |date=February 23, 1950 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\t\n\n== External links ==\n* {{tcmdb title|id=15982}}\n* {{IMDb title|0042449|Father Is a Bachelor}}\n* {{amg movie|91116}}\n* {{AFI film|id=26310|title=Father Is a Bachelor}}\n\n{{Norman Foster}}\n[[Category:1950 films]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about orphans]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Clarityfiend", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSongs:minor rephrasing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Father_Is_a_Bachelor"}
